White Wine Quality Between Harmfulness and Benefit By Exploring Physicochemical Properties Data

Introduction

The aim of this project is describe the physicochemical properties to try specifying which of them affect white wine quality through exploratory data analysis of a dataset containing attributes for 4898 white wine variants. The dataset is related to White Wine of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. For more details, consult: http://www.vinhoverde.pt/en/ or the reference [Cortez et al., 2009]. Due to privacy and logistic issues, only physicochemical (inputs) and sensory (the output) variables are available (e.g.there is no data about grape types, wine brand, wine selling price, etc.).

  • Number of Instances (obs.): 4898.
  • Number of Attributes (variables): 11 + output attribute + serial No (x var.)

Fixed acidity (Tartaric acid - g/dm^3): Most acids involved in wine are fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily). The fixed acidity follows a normal distribution with mean 6.855 (the median 6.800 g/dm^3) and some outliers found over 8.8 and under 4.8. 75% of wine is below 7.3 g/dm^3.

The plot got more readable by removing some outliers in the right side of the plot. Now, The histogram looks like approximately normal distribution.

Volatile acidity (Acetic acid - g/dm^3): The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste. The volatile acidity has some outliers over 0.49 and under 0.05. The 75% of the data is below 0.32 g/dm^3.

The trimmed volatile acidity distribution appears right skewed with mean in 0.28 g/dm^3.

The trimmed Citric acid looks approximately normal distribution with unusual peak in 0.49 g/dm^3, we can consider it as anomaly.

pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3 - 4 on the pH scale. It means moderately acidic. Outliers are found over 3.565 and under 2.805 and maximum acidic level is 3.82.

The histogram is skewed a little bit to right but it is nearly normal with mean 3.188 and median 3.180.

Residual sugar: The amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 g/liter (g/dm^3) and wines with greater than 45 g/L are considered sweet. Most wine lie in 1 and 20 g/dm^3. Outliers are found in 23, 26, 32 and 66. lets remove outliers ..

Free sulfur dioxide: The free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it advances microbial growth and the oxidation of wine. It has many outliers from 85 to 289 mg/dm^3 as a maximum value. Lets trim it.

It is slightly right skewed but approximately normal and one peak at 29 mg/dm^3 (0.029 g/dm^3).

Total sulfur dioxide is amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm (1 ppm = 1 mg/dm^3) using Google, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine. I found 46 of wine less than 50 ppm, So I asked, if SO2 becomes clear in smell and taste, is this good quality or bad quality of wine? It has many outliers greater than 255 and below 19 mg/dm^3, with maximum 440 and minimum 9 mg/dm^3.

Hint: (According to Wikipedia article) In recent studies white wine (which contains high levels of Sulfur dioxide) was indicated to have some cardiovascular benefits and this makes me excited to investigate the effect of Sulfur dioxide levels (which is considered a health criterion) on quality of wine. Well see.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

This dataset contains 4,898 records of white wine data with 12 variables, 11 input variables based on physicochemical properties which affect wine quality and 1 output variable which is the quality of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I think quality is the main feature in this dataset because it is a criterion of wine goodness. I want to check all the other variables combinations, which of them are affecting the quality the most. Quality scores (between 0 and 10) values range (in the dataset) between 3 as minimum and 9 as maximum score. There are no observations in scores 1, 2 and 10. Most frequent quality score is in 6 score and the least frequent is in 9 score. Since the most frequent quality scores are in the three columns (5, 6 and 7) in the middle, does this indicate that the quality evaluation is based on the experts opinions of taste and smell? Or on a specific technical basis depending on the physical or chemical properties of the wine?. So, this is what I will investigate in the next section.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I want to investigate the two variables (residual sugar and alcohol) because I read about them that they are affecting the quality of wine and I observed that they have clearly different distributions than the other variables. Also I want to do more investigations on some variables (Total Sulfur dioxide, Density, Volatile acidity, Citric acid and pH) which I think they are important for their influence (smell and taste) on wine quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I didnt need to create any new variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I converted quality column as a factor variable to help me in exploration. When plotting histograms of the variables, I applied the xlim to limit the lower and upper x-axis value to remove outliers and to focus on the main values for better visualizations and to see clearer distributions of these variables. Also, I log-transformed the right skewed Residual Sugar distribution to zoom in the small values of data.

The fixed acidity concentration shows negative moderate correlation with pH.

The wine quality increases when volatile acidity decreases, this is what I expected because when (volatile acidity) increases it can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

Also, better quality wines seem to have smaller fixed acidifies on average. This is what I expected too because if pH decreases, fixed acidity decreases.

Except for wines with quality score 3, the median pH increases (Acidity decreases) along with quality score. So, from the last three visualizations I conclude that as acidity decreases quality increases.

The wine quality increases when chlorides decrease.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

I found quality has positive moderate correlation with alcohol and I found also quality has negative correlation with residual.sugar, I found these results make sense because fermentation process is the conversion of sugar to alcohol so sugar and alcohol have negative correlation. quality has negative correlation with density. I found also that quality has negative correlation with total sulfur dioxide which makes me observe that quality rating is not based on the healthy components (like sulfur dioxide). There are 3 variables to represent acidity quantity (pH, fixed acidity and volatile acidity) both fixed acidity and volatile acidity have negative correlation with quality and pH has positive correlation (acidity decreases) with quality, so the 3 variables say the quality has negative correlation with acidity. Finally I found also quality has negative correlation with chlorides.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

One of the exciting relationships that I found is alcohol has negative correlation with total sulfur dioxide which may mean as the healthy components (sulfur dioxide) increases the harmful components (alcohol) decreases. Residual sugar has negative correlation with alcohol due to fermentation process as explained before. pH has negative correlation with fixed acidity and volatile acidity and this is expected because pH scale decreases as acidity increases. Also I found density has negative correlation with alcohol and positive correlation with sugar and this is expected as sugar is always decreases as alcohol increases (Fermentation).

Multivariate Plots Section

I started with this plot because it shows the relation between the main 3 features affecting the wine quality (having the biggest correlation coefficients in the Bi-variate section) so we can conclude that these 3 features are the main focus of the experts to rate the wine quality. The visualization shows two observations: the first is sweeter wine has more density, the second is wine with the same sweetness has larger percentage of alcohol when density increases.And the reverse is correct.

The plot shows a moderate negative correlation between (pH and fixed.acidity) and this is expected because pH is a measure for acidity (pH decreases as acidity increases). I can justify the gathering of the data points in this specific area and not spread because most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale. Finally I observed that citric acid has no clear trend which means that it has no significant effect on pH of wine.

The 2 plots show a moderate negative correlation (-0.45) between (Total sulfur dioxide and alcohol). Generally, I noticed the spread of the green and blue colors among the data points which represent quality scores (5,6 and 7) and this observation makes sense as in the quality variable distribution big number of data points are in scores (5,6 and 7) and if the other scores (3, 4, 8 and 9) have also a big number of data points we could have captured a more clear trend of quality scores than the shown plot. Finally, the captured trend of quality score is as the alcohol increases the quality score increases but total sulfur dioxide decreases.

From this plot I can conclude that as sugar increases alcohol decreases which shows that some people prefer high levels of sugar and the other people prefer low levels of sugar and according to my readings the manufacturers take this point in consideration during fermentation process so it needs accurate tools.

Reflection

Beside data analysis I made a lot of exploration and reading about the wine components and types to be able to describe the relations between variables and to determine the main features of concern during analysis that was because in my culture drinking wine is not popular among people and also it is known that wine has harmful effects more than its benefits, so I was excited to check this by myself through data analysis. The surprising result I concluded was that as the harmful components (alcohol) increases the healthy components (total sulfur dioxide) decreases. The struggles that I faced is the relatively low number of data points, so capturing trends among the variables was not an easy task. In the future I am so interested to repeat this analysis if there are dataset available with large number of data points.
